# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1966-finnish-parliamentary-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in the Grand Duchy of Finland on 15 and 16 March 1907.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] They were the first parliamentary election in which members were elected to the new Parliament of Finland by universal suffrage and the first in the world in which female members were elected.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The election followed the parliamentary reform of 1906 which replaced the Diet of Finland, which was based on the Estates and had its institutional roots in the period of Swedish reign, with a modern unicameral parliament of 200 MPs.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The reform was agreed upon after a general strike in Finland in 1905 during which demands for a parliamentary reform arose especially among the Socialists.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] This coincided with similar development in Russia which too saw a general strike and, after the Russo-Japanese War, the birth of a new institution, the Duma.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] This background explains why Emperor Nicholas II of Russia allowed parliamentary reform in Finland.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] All political factions of Finland reached an agreement on the reform and the first elections were set for 1907.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The 1906 reform ended the first period of attempted Russification in the Grand Duchy of Finland which had begun in 1899 and seen such dramatic episodes as the assassination of Nikolai Bobrikov, the Governor-General of Finland, in 1904.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] This kind of institution had become quite ancient by the early years of the 20th century.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The new unicameral parliament was to have 200 MPs, all elected by universal and equal suffrage of citizens over 24 years of age.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Women as well were allowed to vote and stand for election; Finnish women were the first in Europe to receive these rights.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Previously only New Zealand and South Australia had approved universal female suffrage, and Finland was the second to grant women the right to stand as candidates.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The voting system was designed to allow voters the choice between a simple list vote and expressing more particular preferences.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] A voter could vote for a party list of candidates by marking it with a red line.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Alternatively, the voter could rank up to three names from among the candidates on any list in order of preference.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Even further, a voter could vote for up to three persons from outside the lists by entering their names.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The D'Hondt method was used to allocate seats after the list votes, preference votes and off-list votes were put together according to a somewhat complex procedure.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The language strife of Finland was an important issue in the late 19th and early 20th century Finnish politics.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Thus the first political parties of Finland, the Finnish Party and the Swedish Party, were born respectively around Fennoman and Svecoman ideas.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] A Liberal party was founded but soon also dissolved.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finnish party was later split into the supporters of the "Old Finns," and the "Young Finns" who founded a party of their own.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] An even more important event was the founding of a Socialist party in 1899.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] First called the Finnish Labour Party, it adopted the name Social Democratic Party of Finland in 1903 and sought the support of the urban working class and the rural landless population.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Universal suffrage was naturally very important for these groups since they had no political power in the Diet of the Estates.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] In 1906 the Agrarian League was founded to represent the interests of peasants and in the same year the Swedish Party adopted its present name, the Swedish People's Party.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The topics of the campaign into the election touched for example social issues and the parties' stances to the Russification attempts.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The results of the first parliamentary election in Finnish history were somewhat a surprise for the traditional parties; the Social Democrats emerged as clear winners, winning 80 of the 200 seats, making them the largest faction in Parliament.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Of the right-wing or centre-right parties the Finnish Party gained the most seats with 59, followed by the Young Finnish Party with 26 and the Swedish People's Party with 24.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Agrarian League won only nine seats but in the following years its support grew rapidly.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] As a result of the election the representatives of workers and the landless people (the Social Democrats) became the largest group in the parliament, whereas previously they had no political representation whatsoever in the legislative body.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Women too gained representation; 19 female MPs were elected.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] They became the first female MPs in the world.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] A few women realised that the women of Finland needed to seize this opportunity and organisation and education would be required.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Newly elected MPs Lucina Hagman and Maikki Friberg together with Olga Oinola, Aldyth Hultin, Mathilda von Troil, Ellinor Ingman-Ivalo, Sofia Streng and Olga Österberg founded the Finnish Women's Association's first branch in Helsinki.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The joy of the Social Democrats over their victory proved to be short lasting.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The second period of attempted Russification in the Grand Duchy of Finland began the following year and the Russian Emperor dissolved the Parliament of Finland on numerous occasions in 1908–1917.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] During World War I the parliament did not convene for a long time.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] Thus the Social Democrats were not able to push through most of their desired reforms during these final years of the period of Finland's autonomy, despite being able to keep their position as the largest party in all elections of this period.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] As a result, many Socialist supporters lost their initially high hopes for the parliament elected by universal suffrage.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] This in turn was one factor among others in the development which led to the Finnish Civil War in 1918.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The 100th anniversary of the first Finnish Parliament was selected as the main motif for a high value commemorative coin, the €2 100th Anniversary of the Finnish Parliamentary commemorative coin, minted in 2006.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] The obverse shows the silhouette of a woman's and a man's hands, and below the hands ballots being inserted in a ballot-box.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] On the reverse, two stylized faces in the centre part, one male and the other female, separated by a thin curved line is depicted.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1907-finnish-parliamentary-election] They symbolize the equality of genders, as does the fact that the pictorial subjects on both sides are equal in respect to the centre of the coin.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in the Grand Duchy of Finland on 1 and 2 July 1908.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Russian Tsar Nicholas II dissolved the first modern and democratic Finnish Parliament after its Speaker, Pehr Evind Svinhufvud, refused, in the Tsar's opinion, to show enough respect for him when speaking at the parliamentary session's opening.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] In 1908, the Russian government restarted its Russification policy in Finland, limiting Finnish self-government.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] Most Finns, including most Finnish parliamentarians, opposed the Russification, but disagreed on the means to effectively oppose it.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democratic Party's supporters hoped for positive results from their party's work in Parliament, such as the growing prosperity of workers and tenant farmers, but would be disappointed during the next several elections.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] The other parliamentary parties, with the partial exception of the Agrarians, considered the Social Democrats' demands, such as an eight-hour workday, too radical to be implemented while Finland was trying to save its self-government.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliament had no official control over the government, which was responsible only to the Tsar and to the Governor-General.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1908-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliament's legislative power was also limited by the Tsar's ability to veto its laws, without a time limit on his consideration whether to veto the laws or not.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1913-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in the Grand Duchy of Finland on 1 and 2 August 1913.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1913-finnish-parliamentary-election] In 1914, the Russian government decided to suspend the Finnish Parliament for the duration of World War I.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1913-finnish-parliamentary-election] They disagreed on the social and economic policies, and thus did not formulate very clear positions on them.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in the Grand Duchy of Finland on 1 and 3 July 1916.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Finnish Parliament had not been in session during the early years of World War I.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Russian army's severe losses to the German army started to awaken among the Finns the hope that they could regain self-government.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Russian government's plan to totally Russify Finland had been leaked to several Finnish newspapers in 1914, and had been heavily criticized.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] Its implementation had been suspended for the duration of the war.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats managed to win their first and so far only parliamentary majority in the Finnish elections by promising more effectively than the bourgeois parties to help the poor and underprivileged people among the Finns.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] For the first time since parliamentary elections started in 1907, the left gained a majority in the parliament, with the Social Democrats winning 103 of 200 seats.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The elections also remain the only time in Finnish history in which a single party won a majority.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Tokoi Senate was formed under Socialist Oskari Tokoi, one of the first *de facto* socialist prime ministers in the world (though his title was Chairman of the Senate).
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats retained their majority until the dissolution of the parliament and subsequent elections in October 1917, when all the opposition parties (the Finnish Party, Young Finns, Swedish People's Party and Agrarians) formed an electoral alliance, the "Bourgeoisie block".
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] In March 1917 the February Revolution essentially forced Tsar Nicholas II, who had the highest authority in the Grand Duchy of Finland, and who could dissolve the Finnish parliament, to refuse any new laws and appoint a governor-general when he abdicated.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] This began an administrative crisis, both for the socialists and the bourgeoisie block, on how to proceed.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Provisional Republican Russian government was still in power and administration continued relatively normally, but domestic issues including rising inflation, food shortages and political radicalism was a daily issue in both cities and the countryside.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The law was passed on 18 July 1917, but was never fully enforced.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] Kerensky and the Petrograd government, still the highest political authority, decided to release a manifesto to break the Finnish Parliament.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] The manifesto declared, that the Russian provisional government was, legally speaking, the highest authority for the Grand Duchy of Finland, unless the Russian parliament or a Russian-based constitutional convention decided otherwise.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] This was a win for the "Bourgeoisie block", because the Valtalaki would have transferred power to a Finnish parliament under socialist control.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] In the October snap elections, right-wing parties united against a common enemy, the Social Democrats, and managed to remove the Social Democrats' parliamentary majority.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1916-finnish-parliamentary-election] This was significant, as the politically divided Finland would go on to declare herself independent in December 1917, with the right-wing controlled Parliament in political control of the nation heading into what would become the Finnish Civil War.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in the Grand Duchy of Finland on 1 and 2 October 1917.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The general voter turnout was higher than in previous elections.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats lost the absolute majority that they had had in the previous two elections (although they, like the other parties, had increased their number of votes in absolute terms).
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] In other words, the "bourgeois" (non-socialist) parties taken together now had more than half the seats.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The elections were the result of the constitutional crisis in Finland caused by the Russian revolution.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] As Russian Tsar Nicholas, head of state in Finland, had abdicated without a successor, the Finnish Parliament stated that it would become the highest power in internal matters.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Russian Provisional Government did not accept this, but ordered premature parliamentary elections, which was thought illegal by the Socialists.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats demanded the quick implementation of eight-hour work day and the quick freeing of tenant farmers.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1917-finnish-parliamentary-election] The bourgeois parties, on average, wanted first to ensure that Finland would become fully independent, and only then to implement such social and economic reforms.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Finland between 1 and 3 March 1919.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democratic Party emerged as the largest in Parliament with 80 of the 200 seats.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] In 1919, Finland was still reeling from the violent and traumatic effects of its Civil War.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] Many Whites (rightists and centrists) felt that a strong national government was necessary to prevent a new civil war.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] Some conservatives, especially monarchists, even wondered if Finland should keep its democracy and universal right to vote.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] For example, Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim, in the White Army's victory parade in Helsinki in May 1918, called for giving the leadership of Finland's to a strong leader, free from partisan wrangling.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] Liberals, such as the first President Kaarlo Juho Ståhlberg, believed that discontent with Finland's political, social and economic order would be removed by making reforms.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] The republican parties (the Social Democrats, Agrarians and Progressives) disagreed on how much power the president should have.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] The monarchist parties (the National Coalition Party and the Swedish People's Party of Finland) wanted a strong presidency if there was going to be a republic at all.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] In the end, enough Finnish voters sided with the republican parties, which also promised significant social reforms, such as the freeing of tenant farmers and the distribution of excess farmland to them.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-parliamentary-election] On 25 July 1919 Ståhlberg defeated Mannerheim in the presidential elections.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Indirect presidential elections were held for the first time in Finland in 1919.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Although the country had declared Prince Frederick Charles of Hesse king on 9 October 1918, he renounced the throne on 14 December.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] The president was elected by Parliament, with Kaarlo Juho Ståhlberg of the National Progressive Party receiving 73% of the vote.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Ståhlberg, a moderate, liberal and reformist politician, who favoured improving the material well-being of workers and other economically poor Finns, received the votes of Social Democrats, Agrarians and Progressives.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] He also firmly supported the new Finnish Republic, and a parliamentary form of government with a strong president as a mediator and a political reserve for politically troubled times.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Mannerheim, an independent right-winger and monarchist, suspected the democratic, republican and parliamentary form of government of producing too partisan political leaders, and of working ineffectively during crises.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Ståhlberg favoured the signing of a peace treaty between Finland and the Soviet Russia, while Mannerheim in the summer of 1919 strongly considered ordering the Finnish army to invade St.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Petersburg to help the Russian Whites in that country's civil war.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1919-finnish-presidential-election] Only the National Coalitioners and Swedish People's Party voted for Mannerheim in this presidential election.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Finland on 20 and 21 March 1966.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democratic Party (SDP) overtook the Centre Party as the largest faction in Parliament.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Rafael Paasio of the SDP subsequently became Prime Minister and formed a popular front government consisting of the SDP, the Centre Party, the People's Democratic League (SKDL), and the Social Democratic Union of Workers and Smallholders (TPSL) in May 1966.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Prior to the elections, Centre Party Prime Minister Johannes Virolainen had led a centre-right coalition government since September 1964.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Meanwhile, Paasio had moved the SDP further to the left in order to attract back voters from the TPSL.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Finnish society was undergoing a period of radical criticism of traditional values, such as Christianity, marriage, parents' authority over their children, teachers' authority over their students, patriotism, and civil servants' (including judges') authority over private citizens.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] The Social Democrats and the SKDL tapped into this discontent at the expense of the centre-right coalition.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] At the same time, leading Social Democrats, such as former Minister of Social Affairs and Minister of the Interior Väinö Leskinen, had promised to support President Kekkonen's foreign policy with regards to the Soviet Union, and his continuance as President.
[src:1966-finnish-parliamentary-election/1966-finnish-parliamentary-election] Overall, the leftist coalition achieved a combined majority (51.0%) of the votes cast in the election.
